<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1904-01-29T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1904-01-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="181" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d181">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Loomis</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Snyder</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1904-01-29"><hi rend="italic">January 29,
                                1904</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>(Replying to Mr. Snyder’s telegram of January 26, Mr. Loomis instructs
                            him that this Government’s attitude remains the same since Department’s
                            telegram of November 11<note n="a" xml:id="d181fna">Printed in <ref target="frus1903#pg_228">Foreign Relations, 1903, p.
                                228</ref>.</note> to Minister Beaupré. Nothing written or verbal to
                            General Reyes would in any way retreat from that position. Mr. Snyder is
                            instructed to verify origin of unfounded rumors.)</p>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>